snippet.textDisplay: i started a relationship when i was 15. he was my everything, my emotional support, and even sometimes (sadly) the only friend i could count on. i felt like we were going to last forever, and every time someone said "aren't you too young to be in a long term relationship?" i said i was happy to have someone to grow up next to. we broke up last year (just before my 20th birthday) and i felt like my whole life shattered. i thought all of my plans for the future fell apart and i didn't knew what to do. my life partner was gone and i felt like i didn't know who i was. and damn right i didn't. i had no fucking clue!! i had spent almost the past 5 years of my life being part of a couple, a 2x1 package deal. i didn't know who i was because i never had to work for that - i was always his girlfriend. it's been almost a year, and i'm still learning. i took up new hobbies. i reconnected with friends. i started to actually think about what i want to be in the future. i went through a tinder phase, still searching validation in being liked by guys (just as Ashley said). it's been hard, but i think about it know and i am happy than i've ever been. not that i wasn't happy in my relationship - i felt so loved, so supported, and we grew up together and it was beautiful. we went to prom together, graduated high school, saw each other get into university. he was my best friend during all of that time, and even now he's the person who knows me the most in the entire world. but right now, i'm truly happy. i'm working on the most important relationship i've ever had - the one with myself. she's a cute, funny, smart girl. she might not have all her shit together now, but she's enjoying the journey. <3

snippet.textDisplay:
This video is so good and insightful and also very timely for me. I needed to hear it right now, so thank you. My story is the opposite: I dated the same person since high school and had an awful breakup 8 years in. Take it from me, you are so so so lucky that you have gone through different relationships, seen different people, and spent that quality time with yourself. The time I spent with my partner was for the most part good, but I totally stopped prioritizing myself. I spent a long time making myself a supporting character in my own life.


I think there is something about being in a heterosexual relationship that encourages women to erase ourselves. Even if we go in with the best of intentions we end up feeling this pressure to let somebody else take the wheel from us, because the messaging we get tells us that this is our purpose in life. Basically, spending time with ourselves to appreciate ourselves is so important, in more than a "me time" kind of way. Bc I get the feeling that we arent really encouraged to know ourselves, let alone to prioritize ourselves. Theres an idea that its somehow selfish, because we are reallocating our valuable time and energy away from the potential man who could be benefitting from it. At least that's my take on it.


Anyway..... I guess feminist ranting is contagious lol. And thank you for this video :)

snippet.textDisplay: It has been proven but is not widely known (because it’s a very unpopular thought) that men do not have a longer reproductive life than women after all. It turns out that the quality of their sperm production degrades after about age 30 and they have a higher risk of having children with autism and Down’s syndrome the older they get. The ticking biological clock does not just apply to women. Scientific American did a big feature on this year’s ago — it is not new information.

snippet.textDisplay:
This valentines day that was also my mom's birthday, the guy I was dating with (over a month) told me he met someome else, by message, doesn't even mention the word "breakup" he just said "I'm sorry" and expected me to end things, obiously I did, and cried a little bit while watching rom-coms, but after that I went to my mom's to sing her happy birthday and enjoy her company. The next day I was already feeling better, I didn't realize he was causing me such stress until I erased him from my life. I'm a helpless romantic, but now I romanticize the idea of my future and how great it can be. Being in love with myself makes it difficult for me to fall easily for somebody else.
Besides, all these dramas are great stories for when I'm older and have someone to listen to them.
